WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.080
And I'll be presenting our data on a combinatorial cell therapy with ORCA-T and allogeneic CAR-T

00:00:07.080 --> 00:00:08.380
for high-risk BALL.

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:16.420
So following up on what Logan said and summarized so beautifully, we know that in the setting

00:00:16.420 --> 00:00:22.140
of autologous CD19 CAR-T cells for BALL, there's low durable remission rates.

00:00:22.140 --> 00:00:26.920
So I'm showing here the data for ZUMA3 with Brexacel and Felix-Obacel.

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:32.440
When we look at those publications for both of these studies, what we find is exactly

00:00:32.440 --> 00:00:37.060
what Logan was saying is that in the patients who retrieved CAR-T cells on those studies,

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:42.080
that the exposure to transplant either pre- or post-CAR-T was about 60%.

00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:48.980
So this is showing us that the patients who are getting CAR-T are getting allotransplant

00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:50.900
at some point during their course of therapy.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:57.000
Our Stanford experience with novel cell therapies is something that I want to highlight just

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:57.100
briefly.

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:01.960
Before getting into the trial, some of you may be familiar with the ORCA-T graft, which

00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:06.920
is a graft engineered strategy that came out of research from the laboratory of Rob Negrin,

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:12.700
where they found that regulatory T cells help to prevent graft versus host disease.

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:18.020
As a result, this was translated to the clinic, to ORCA-Bio, and they have a phase three clinical

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:21.260
trial that was just published in Blood earlier this year.

00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:26.860
Essentially, the approach with this graft engineering strategy allows for the isolation

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:27.000
of the graft.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.900
So this is just a demonstration of the hematopoietic stem cells and the regulatory T cells, as

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:37.300
well as T-cons, such that the Tregs and HSPCs are delivered or administered on day zero

00:01:37.300 --> 00:01:39.280
and T-cons on day two.

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:44.260
Another cell therapy that I want to highlight, which is relevant to the clinical trial that

00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:49.840
I'm about to report on, is an autologous bispecific CD1922 CAR that came out of Crystal

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:50.600
Mackel's lab.

00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:54.560
It's a CAR for which we readily had vector for manufacturing at Stanford.

00:01:55.120 --> 00:01:56.800
The publication from that.

00:01:56.880 --> 00:02:04.020
Nature Medicine in 2021 did show in the subset of patients with BALL, 17 patients who received

00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:12.060
BALL on that trial, that the overall response rate was 100% with a CR of 88%, but the durable

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:13.460
remission was also limited.

00:02:13.940 --> 00:02:17.560
And one of the reasons for that, when they did deeper analysis of the CAR signaling,

00:02:17.760 --> 00:02:22.400
is that they found that, in fact, the CAR predominantly signaled through CD19 and the

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:23.980
CD22 signaling was limited.

00:02:23.980 --> 00:02:26.700
So it was effectively a CD1941BB CAR.

00:02:26.760 --> 00:02:33.220
But, because we had that vector readily available, we wanted to look at these two approaches

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:34.020
in combination.

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:41.440
And part of that rationale or desire to combine allotransplant and CAR-T as a post-transplant

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:46.780
prophylaxis against relapse came from some preclinical data from my time as a postdoc

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:51.700
at Memorial Sloan Kettering in the lab of Marcel Vandenbrink, where we found that

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:56.600
administration of CAR-T cells in the post-transplant setting had a low signal of

00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:57.640
graft-versus-host disease.

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:00.060
So we thought this was a viable strategy to translate.

00:03:01.180 --> 00:03:06.860
As a result, we developed this allocar transplant, or we call it ACT, and this is ACT-1 because

00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:11.560
we're now working on ACT-2, the strategy of combining allocar with transplant.

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:16.940
So our hypothesis was that for patients with high-risk BALL who received a myeloblative

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:21.340
ORCA-T from a matched-related or unrelated donor, and I'll highlight that we did

00:03:21.340 --> 00:03:26.380
incorporate unrelated donors as well because we amended our protocol to include donors,

00:03:26.480 --> 00:03:27.360
not just from the NMVP.

00:03:27.920 --> 00:03:32.780
We hypothesized that the addition of the donor CAR-T cells would augment graft-versus-leukemia

00:03:32.780 --> 00:03:38.220
without increasing acute graft-versus-host disease, grade 3 or 4, or graft failure.

00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:44.900
Our primary endpoint was to assess the incidence of engraftment without grade 3 to 4 GVHD at

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:45.460
day 42.

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:47.380
You can see our key secondary endpoints.

00:03:47.920 --> 00:03:49.600
We also incorporated others.

00:03:49.820 --> 00:03:56.200
And key eligibility was adult patients, good performance status, high-risk BALL features who had,

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:57.960
and eligible matched donor.

00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:00.940
And these are the three CAR-T cell doses.

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:06.440
So the lowest dose was 1 times 10 to the 6 CAR-positive cells per kilogram, all the way up

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:11.620
to the dose level 3, 3 times 10 to the 6, and we used a Bayesian dose escalation design.

00:04:13.140 --> 00:04:14.960
So here is the strategy.

00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:17.400
So I'll walk you through because it is a bit complex.

00:04:17.400 --> 00:04:21.280
So for our eligible donors, they underwent two cell collections.

00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:26.240
The first was a leukophoresis, so that was steady state, and those leukophoresis,

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:29.420
products were then used for the CAR-T manufacturing.

00:04:29.780 --> 00:04:37.460
Next, the donor underwent a GCSF-mobilized apheresis, which was used for the ORCA-T engineering.

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:44.240
At the same time, the eligible donor, patients eligible for myeloblative conditioning,

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:48.640
underwent their myeloblative conditioning with TBI, PSI, or bufluthaotepa.

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:56.120
And then you can see day 0 got the stem cells and Tregs, day 2, the Tcons, which again is a part of the

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:59.840
approach, and we added on to day 2, CAR-T cell infusion.

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:04.600
Day 3 was tacrolimus, and then again, our safety endpoint in day 42.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:15.460
So for the inclusion, we enrolled 18 patients, of which 16 got the combined cell therapies.

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:21.200
One patient had CAR manufacturing and then couldn't proceed because of infectious complications,

00:05:21.860 --> 00:05:26.100
and then that was before they even got the transplant, and then there was one,

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:29.800
patient who got a transplant and no CAR-T because the day before the CAR-T infusion,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.900
she had a metanuma virus infection and for that reason didn't get the CAR-T.

00:05:34.540 --> 00:05:39.380
So here are the characteristics of the patients who were included, median age of 31,

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:45.020
majority were Hispanic, which really tracks with the BALL population in California, so

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:46.960
70% were Hispanic.

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:52.040
The high-risk features that you see could have been in multiple high-risk features in a patient,

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:55.740
those are noted there, and prior therapies of note.

00:05:55.980 --> 00:05:58.840
I want to just show that the majority of the patients had a matched sibling donor.

00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:08.060
So in terms of the safety, no delays in engraftment, you can see the numbers of acute and chronic

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:13.980
graft-versus-host disease, so all low-grade and resolved patients are on no ongoing immune

00:06:13.980 --> 00:06:14.820
suppression for that.

00:06:15.160 --> 00:06:20.640
Low rates of CRS and ICANS, and one patient developed, you know, occlusive disease and

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:25.060
subsequently had normal resolution of hepatic function at day 42.

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:34.040
Fifteen of the patients had MRD-negative CR and two patients had an MRD-positive CR by

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:39.280
clonoseq, but otherwise BCR-able and fluocytometry-negative, and this data was just

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:43.340
recently updated with a date cutoff of March 15th.

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:48.580
In terms of the median follow-up, we have about a year and a half of median follow-up.

00:06:48.580 --> 00:06:54.020
All patients are surviving and disease-free survival is also 100%.

00:06:54.780 --> 00:06:55.740
Our long-term...

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:58.520
Our longest patient is out to almost three years.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:06.340
So here is a swimmer's plot showing the 100% MRD-negativity by fluocytometry, BCR-able,

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:10.600
and clonoseq, and I just want to draw your attention to a couple of things on this.

00:07:10.600 --> 00:07:16.200
So baseline, seven patients were MRD-positive, one patient had active disease, and so in

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:22.980
the two that were MRD-positive post-transplant, subjects four and subject 11, at the last

00:07:22.980 --> 00:07:25.460
clonoseq assessments, they are now clonoseq zero.

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:28.400
So there's a lot of evidence that that's not true, and I think it's important to keep

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:29.400
that in mind as well.

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:31.860
We do note that there is long-term CAR-T cell persistence.

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:38.220
So by fluocytometry in the top line, the majority of those cells that are persisting are the

00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:42.420
CD4 subset, which really tracks with data that we've seen from long-term CAR-T cell

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:43.420
persistence.

00:07:43.420 --> 00:07:48.340
We're in the process of analyzing additional samples so we can have more robust numbers

00:07:48.340 --> 00:07:53.840
for that analysis, and also for the qPCR from a quantitative perspective, they're showing

00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:55.500
long-term persistence.

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:59.420
QPCR and CAR facts are correlating well.

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:03.940
We didn't see any issues with donor chimerism, as you can see here, both for CD3 and whole

00:08:03.940 --> 00:08:04.940
blood.

00:08:04.940 --> 00:08:11.300
So in summary, we have the understanding that most adults with high-risk BALL who receive

00:08:11.300 --> 00:08:16.140
CAR also received a synchronous allotransplant during their treatment course, that in adults

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:21.620
with high-risk BALL, ACT with allocar and ORCA-T led to durable remission.

00:08:21.620 --> 00:08:25.380
So we believe that ACT is a rational approach that merits further investigation.

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:30.760
For high-risk B-cell malignancies, as well as other malignancies, correlative data suggests

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:35.060
that these CARs are persisting beyond one year, and so now we're going to be doing some deeper

00:08:35.060 --> 00:08:36.620
correlative analysis.

00:08:36.620 --> 00:08:39.540
With that, I would like to acknowledge Lori Muffley, the PI of the study.

00:08:39.540 --> 00:08:41.280
I am the IND holder.

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:46.220
Also, our faculty and funding sources and manufacturing, etc.

00:08:46.220 --> 00:08:46.700
Thank you so much.
